  "footnotes": [
    "D'mt Kingdom (c.8th–5th c. BCE): One of the earliest known states in sub-Saharan Africa, centred at Ye'ha in Tigray; used a South Arabian script and may have had Sabaean connections; precursor to the Aksumite state.",
    "Aksumite Kingdom (c.100–940 CE): One of the great powers of Late Antiquity; controlled the Red Sea trade; converted to Christianity (c.330 CE under King Ezana); minted its own coins; its steles (obelisks) still stand at Aksum.",
    "Zagwe Dynasty (c.900–1270): Cushitic dynasty that replaced Aksum; built the famous rock-hewn churches of Lalibela (12th c.); considered themselves legitimate Christian rulers but were later depicted as usurpers by Solomonic historians.",
    "Adal-Ethiopian War / Grañ (1529–1543): Ahmad ibn Ibrahim al-Ghazi (called 'Grañ' — the left-handed) led an Adal Sultanate jihad that conquered most of Ethiopia; reversed only with Portuguese military aid (Battle of Wayna Daga, 1543).",
    "Battle of Adwa (1896): Ethiopian forces under Menelik II decisively defeated the Italian army; the first major African victory over a European colonial power; secured Ethiopian independence.",
    "Derg (1974–1991): Military junta that deposed Haile Selassie; declared Marxist-Leninist state; responsible for Red Terror (1977–78) killing thousands; defeated by EPRDF coalition after prolonged civil war.",
    "Tigray War (2020–2022): Armed conflict between the Ethiopian federal government (allied with Eritrea) and the Tigray People's Liberation Front (TPLF); estimated 300,000–600,000 deaths; ended with Pretoria Agreement (November 2022)."
  ]
